07693nam a22014895i 9780691184050DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911840507 a10.1515/97806911840502doi  a(DE-B1597)501772  a(OCoLC)1057671257  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHB1-130 7aBUS0230002bisacsh1 aColander, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhere Economics Went Wrong :bChicago's Abandonment of Classical Liberalism /cDavid Colander, Craig Freedman. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- t1. Sweet Science: Engineering a New Approach to Economic Policy -- t2. A Classical Garden of Liberal Economics: Policy versus Abstraction -- t3. Planting the Seeds of a Chicago Tradition -- t4. Ashes and Diamonds: The Rise of the Chicago School -- t5. What Has Chicago Wrought? Painting Policy by the Numbers -- t6. Economic Policy Becomes a Science: The Rise of Welfare Economics, and the Chicago Alternative -- t7. Roads Not Taken: The Stillborn Virginia School of Economics -- t8. The Classical Liberal "Argumentation for the Sake of Heaven" Alternative -- t9. The Art and Craft of Economics: The Classical Liberal Attitude -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow modern economics abandoned classical liberalism and lost its wayMilton Friedman once predicted that advances in scientific economics would resolve debates about whether raising the minimum wage is good policy. Decades later, Friedman's prediction has not come true. In Where Economics Went Wrong, David Colander and Craig Freedman argue that it never will. Why? Because economic policy, when done correctly, is an art and a craft. It is not, and cannot be, a science. The authors explain why classical liberal economists understood this essential difference, why modern economists abandoned it, and why now is the time for the profession to return to its classical liberal roots.Carefully distinguishing policy from science and theory, classical liberal economists emphasized values and context, treating economic policy analysis as a moral science where a dialogue of sensibilities and judgments allowed for the same scientific basis to arrive at a variety of policy recommendations. Using the University of Chicago-one of the last bastions of classical liberal economics-as a case study, Colander and Freedman examine how both the MIT and Chicago variants of modern economics eschewed classical liberalism in their attempt to make economic policy analysis a science. By examining the way in which the discipline managed to lose its bearings, the authors delve into such issues as the development of welfare economics in relation to economic science, alternative voices within the Chicago School, and exactly how Friedman got it wrong.Contending that the division between science and prescription needs to be restored, Where Economics Went Wrong makes the case for a more nuanced and self-aware policy analysis by economists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aComparative economics. 0aEconomic policy. 0aLiberalism. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh  aAaron Director.  aAlvin Roth.  aAmartya Sen.  aAriel Rubinstein.  aBuchanan political economy.  aChicago Economics Department.  aChicago School of Economics.  aChicago School.  aChicago economics.  aChicago tradition.  aChicago.  aClassical Liberal attitude.  aClassical Liberal methodology.  aClassical Liberalism.  aClassical Liberals.  aCoasian institutionalist approach.  aDani R